<DOC><DOCNO> AP880804-0054 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-88 1356EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Refugees     08-04 0193</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Refugees,0198</SECOND><HEAD>No Agreement Reached At Boat People Talks</HEAD><DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Hong Kong and Hanoi have not reached anysolutions on repatriating Vietnamese refugees, but they agreed tomeet again soon, a government statement said Thursday.   The statement said meetings this week between the twogovernments regarding repatriating Vietnamese boat people were``open and friendly.''   Both sides agreed the historical and social causes of theoutflow were complex but ``realistic and effective measures tobring it to an end were urgently required,'' the statement said. Itdid not elaborate on when future meetings might be held.   Earlier Thursday, Vietnamese foreign minister Nguyen Co Thachtold reporters after talks with the Thai government that Vietnamwill take back all people who wish to return home after fleeing byboat.   On June 16, Hong Kong started to curb surging arrivals ofVietnamese boat people by ending its open-door policy. Vietnamesewho cannot prove they are fleeing political persecution areconsidered illegal immigrants subject to repatriation.   About 7,000 Vietnamese have sailed into Hong Kong since thepolicy came into effect and the number of Vietnamese staying inHong Kong camps is approaching 23,000.</TEXT></DOC>